Walmart_Retail_Forecasting

Time Series Analysis and Forecasting Project¶

Forecasting the Weekly Sales of a retail store and how it's impacted by the Holidays and Special events like Super Bowl¶

Problem Statement:¶

Retail industry is one of the fast paced industry where concepts like inventory optimization, network optimization, sales/demand forecasting play critical role. The product sales is heavily dependent on the customers' attention which is quite fickle and can be captured by the competitor at the drop of the hat. For example, if the product is not on the shelf, if the product cost is higher than the competitors' price or if the arrival of an online order is longer than the competitors'. For customer retention and increasing the profits, it is critical to forecast the demand as accurately as possible. It'll minimize the cost in the form of warehouse inventory and will also tackle the sudden demand surges during holidays and special events like the super bowl.

Project Aim:¶

The aim of the project is:

  • To develop a statistical model which defines the relation between the weekly sales and predictors,
  • Use this model to forecast the weekly demands as accurately as possible, and
  • Observe the effect of the holidays/special events on the demand forecast.

Project Plan:¶

  • Exploring and understanding the train dataset.
  • Preprocessing the dataset by cleaning, manipulating the columns, wherever applicable.
  • Using the cleaned dataset for the most efficient data modeling.
  • Applying various regression algorithms on the data model to predict the weekly demand.
  • Using the ARIMA/Exponential smoothing models before applying various regression algorithms for demand forecasting.
  • Comparing the prediction/forecasting metric RMSE of all the algorithms and choosing the best algorithm.
  • Predicting the weekly sales of the data in the test dataset.

About the dataset:¶

The dataset is split in 3 different .csv files. Each of the three .csv files are a piece of information regarding Walmart's weekly sales. The 3 files described are as follows:

  • features.csv: This file contains additional data related to the store, department, and regional activity for the given dates. It contains the following fields:
    • Store Number.
    • Date of sale.
    • Temperature.
    • Fuel Price.
    • Markdown 1 to 5.
    • Consumer Price Index (CPI).

  • Stores.csv: This file contains anonymized information about the 45 stores, indicating the type and size of the store:

    • Store.
    • Type.
    • Size.

  • train.csv: This is the historical training data, which covers 2010–02–05 to 2012–11–01. Within this file you will find the following fields:

    • Store.
    • Dept.
    • date.
    • Weekly_Sales.
    • Is_Holiday.
  • test.csv: This file is identical to train.csv, except the weekly sales is withheld .

Obeservations on the df_store dataframe:¶

  • It appears from the scatter plot and the boxplot that there is significant difference between the sizes of the three types of stores. Type 'A' store being the largest and the Type 'C' stores being the smallest.
  • Also, the variation in the size of the type 'A' is higher than the variation in the size of type 'C'.
  • There are outliers in the type 'A' size as the 50% percentile or the median is different from the mean of the box plot.
  • The outliers of the type 'A' are less than the mean. The 25%, 50%, 75% percentiles and the max are comparable but the min is different.

Either the outliers have been wrongly named as type 'A' or they might have been changed from previously 'C' type due to some business decision. We'll keep the table as it was.

Observation on the df_features dataframe:¶

  • There are many null values in the columns MarkDown1 to MarkDown5, CPI and Unemployement of the dataset. The null values in the MarkDown2 column is the highest.
  • The IsHoliday column seems to have a certain degree of correlation with the columns MarkDown1 to MarkDown4 but it doesn't have any significant correlation with the MarkDown5 column.
  • MarkDown1 and MarkDown4 are highly correlated (~82%). We might have to drop one of the columns to avoid multicollinearity.
  • Temperature is correlated to MarkDown2. Is it possible that the store is giving discount or promoting a product when the temperature is high outside. We need to check the relation between the temperature, MarkDown2 and the date to find out if this is true.
  • MarkDown2 and MarkDown3 are also correlated to IsHoliday column.
  • MarkDown5 doesn't have a significant correlation with any of the other predictors.
  • Understandably, the IsHoliday column is disproportionately distributed.

Observations on the df_train dataframe:¶

  • The dataset is clean and has no null values in any of the columns.
  • There seem to be outliers in the Weekly_Sales column. Negative Sales is impossible and there seems to be extremely high sales since there is vast difference between the 25%, 50%, 75% and the max value of the weekly sales.
  • There seems to be higher sales during the holidays/special days but the difference from the above boxplot doesn't seem to be obviously significant. There is only 7% increase in the average sales on holidays and regular days but the number of holidays are very low as compared to the regular days still the sales are comparable thus the stores must be busy during the holiday season or on special days.
  • There are 45 stores and all of them are uniquely numbered from 1 to 45.
  • There are 81 departments and there are number from 1 to 99. Some of the in between values of 60s, 70s and 80s are missing.
  • There are ~1500 rows with Sales value either 0 or less which is not possible. We might need to drop these rows as we can't impute 0 either as 0 sales also makes no sense if spread across several departments.
  • From the sales plot, a seasonality can be observed

Observation on the year on year comparison of monthly sales:¶

  • The sale increased dramatically from Jan to Feb which could be correlated to the Super Bowl week.
  • The sales is consistent between the months of 2 and 8.
  • The sales dips from 8 to the 10th month then it increases drastically from 10 to 12th month which is understandble due to the holiday season and especially the Black Friday Sale in the Thanksgiving week.
  • The sales of the year 2011 is less than the sales of the year 2010 all through the year except for month of November. So, as compared to 2010, the overall sales of the year 2011 is less.
  • The 2012 sales looks promising till the 10th month which is comparable to the year 2010's sales.
  • The data for 2012's Nov and Dec months is in the test.csv file as the test set.

Note:¶

Since the R2 value is too low, Linear Regression wouldn't perform well even if the columns are scaled. Also, from the above summary, all except 'IsHoliday' column are significant. We can now directly move on to Tree-based regression algorithms. The tree-based algorithms wouldn't be sensitive to the scales of the columns in the dataset.

There are 18 hyperparameters and optimizing all of them for the best result would take a lot of computational power which I don't have on my laptop, so I'll use only the following 6 hyperparameters for the tuning purpose:

1) n_estimators - The number of trees in the random forest. 2) max_features - Maximum number of predictors considered for splitting a node. 3) max_depth - Maximum number of levels in each of the n_estimators decision tree. 4) min_sample_split - Minimum number of data rows placed in a node before it's split. 5) min_samples_leaf - Minimum number of data rows allowed in a leaf node. 6) bootstrap - Method for sampling data points (with or without replacement).

We'll create a grid of the 6 hyperparameters listed above for the RandomizedSearchCV to search for the optimized combination of the hyperparameters. Since the run time was large I did only 3 iterations and used cross validation = 2.

In [97]:
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV

# Number of trees in random forest
n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 200, stop = 2000, num = 10)]

# Number of features to consider at every split
max_features = ['auto', 'sqrt']

# Maximum number of levels in tree
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(10, 110, num = 11)]
max_depth.append(None)

# Minimum number of samples required to split a node
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]

# Minimum number of samples required at each leaf node
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]

# Method of selecting samples for training each tree
bootstrap = [True, False]

# Create the random grid
random_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,
               'max_features': max_features,
               'max_depth': max_depth,
               'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
               'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf,
               'bootstrap': bootstrap}

# Use the random grid to search for best hyperparameters

Both the plots clearly show some seasonality:

  • Right before, January there is a spike in the sales and in January there is a dip in the sales.
  • For the month of July to December, the sales is similar for all the 3 years.

But, I feel that the weekly sales is better than the monthly sales dataset as monthly sales looses the granularity as seen in the plot. For example, the twin peak in the month of Nov and Dec vanishes in the average monthly sales plot but weekly sales plot still has it.

I will use the average weekly sales dataset for further analysis and application of algorithms.

I'm already aware that there is seasonality in the data so I'll not apply the Moving Average or the Simple Exponential Smoothing techniques for this dataset.

I'll use the ADFuller test on then dataset to find whether the time series is stationary.
